{"id":"1906.03947","submitter":"Nikodem Poplawski","authors":"Nikodem J. Pop{\\l}awski","title":"Non-particle dark matter from Hubble parameter","comments":"3 pages; published version","journal-ref":"Eur. Phys. J. C 79, 734 (2019)","doi":"10.1140/epjc/s10052-019-7230-5","report-no":null,"categories":"physics.gen-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  The measurements of the Hubble parameter using the cosmic microwave\nbackground radiation appear to be inconsistent with the measurements of this\nparameter using Cepheid variable stars. This inconsistency may be a result of\nusing the $\\Lambda$CDM cosmology, which assumes pressureless dark matter, in\nextrapolating the data from the recombination time to the present time. We show\nthat both measurements are consistent if dark matter satisfies an equation of\nstate in which the pressure $p$ and the energy density $\\epsilon$ are related\nby $p=w\\epsilon$ with a negative value of $w$. The data give $w\\approx -0.01$.\nThe negative value of $w$ indicates that dark matter would not be formed by\nparticles, which is consistent with the lack of experimental evidence for them.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 29 May 2019 18:27:12 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Fri, 22 Jan 2021 18:28:38 GMT"}],"update_date":"2021-01-25"}
